92","1539":"1539","England":"England","Hanningfield, Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Carew Chapel, St. Mary's, Beddington, Surrey, England":"Beddington, Surrey, England","Beddington, Surrey, England":"Beddington, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carew","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, James Patrick, Kieran.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire): habitational name from any of various minor places in Wales, in particular one near Pembroke with a major castle, named from Welsh <i>caer</i> ‘fort’ + <i>rhiw</i> ‘hill, slope’. The surname was taken to Ireland soon after the Norman invasion of England and was Gaelicized as <b>de Carrún</b>. In the 16th century a family called <i>Carew</i> from Devon played an important part in establishing the Tudor administration in Ireland.","Cornish (Somerset and Devon): from the cognate Cornish word <i>kerrow</i> (plural of <i>ker</i> ‘fort’), which occurs seven times as a placename in Cornwall."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Carew of Beddington was born in 1469, in Beddington, Surrey, England, his father, James Carew, Esq., was 35 and his mother, Eleanor Hoo, was 20. He married Malyn Oxenbridge. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died on 18 May 1520, in Beddington, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 51, and was buried in Beddington, Surrey, England."},"et":{"1469–18 May 1520":"1469–18. mai 1520","1469–1520":"1469–1520","1473–1544":"1473–1544","1489–1523":"1489–1523","1496–1539":"1496–1539","1510–Female":"1510–Surnud","1435–1492":"1435–1492","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","18 May 1520":"18. mai 1520","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1492":"1492","1469":"1469","1435":"1435","1523":"1523","1489":"1489","1544":"1544","1510":"1510","1520":"1520","1496":"1496","8 December 1492":"8. detsember 1492","1539":"1539","England":"England","Hanningfield, Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Carew Chapel, St. Mary's, Beddington, Surrey, England":"Beddington, Surrey, England","Beddington, Surrey, England":"Beddington, Surrey